Yes! You can implement dynamic queries while using the Azure Cosmos SDK with SQL queries stored in properties files. The key idea is to load queries dynamically from the properties file and construct them dynamically at runtime.

🔥 Approach: Using Cosmos SDK with Dynamic SQL Queries

Instead of writing static queries, we will build dynamic queries at runtime based on user input.

1️⃣ Store SQL Queries in queries.properties

Define the base query and conditional query parts.

baseQuery=SELECT * FROM c WHERE 1=1
filterByParam1= AND c.param1 = @param1
filterByParam2= AND c.param2 = @param2
filterByParam3= AND c.param3 = @param3
filterByParam4= AND c.param4 = @param4
filterByParam5= AND c.param5 = @param5

	•	baseQuery is always included.
	•	Other filters are conditionally added if the corresponding parameters are provided.

2️⃣ Load Queries from Properties File

Create a QueryConfig.java class to read queries dynamically.

@Configuration
public class QueryConfig {
    private final Properties queries = new Properties();

    @PostConstruct
    public void loadQueries() throws IOException {
        ClassPathResource resource = new ClassPathResource("queries.properties");
        queries.load(resource.getInputStream());
    }

    public String getQuery(String key) {
        return queries.getProperty(key);
    }
}

	•	Loads SQL queries at application startup.
	•	Allows easy modifications without redeploying code.

3️⃣ Implement Dynamic Query Execution in Repository

We will use Cosmos SDK to build queries dynamically.

@Repository
public class MyEntityCosmosRepository {

    @Autowired
    private CosmosAsyncContainer cosmosContainer;

    @Autowired
    private QueryConfig queryConfig;

    public List<MyEntity> searchWithDynamicQuery(SearchConditionsDTO searchConditions) {
        StringBuilder queryBuilder = new StringBuilder(queryConfig.getQuery("baseQuery"));
        Map<String, Object> params = new HashMap<>();

        if (StringUtils.hasText(searchConditions.getParam1())) {
            queryBuilder.append(queryConfig.getQuery("filterByParam1"));
            params.put("@param1", searchConditions.getParam1());
        }
        if (StringUtils.hasText(searchConditions.getParam2())) {
            queryBuilder.append(queryConfig.getQuery("filterByParam2"));
            params.put("@param2", searchConditions.getParam2());
        }
        if (StringUtils.hasText(searchConditions.getParam3())) {
            queryBuilder.append(queryConfig.getQuery("filterByParam3"));
            params.put("@param3", searchConditions.getParam3());
        }
        if (StringUtils.hasText(searchConditions.getParam4())) {
            queryBuilder.append(queryConfig.getQuery("filterByParam4"));
            params.put("@param4", searchConditions.getParam4());
        }
        if (StringUtils.hasText(searchConditions.getParam5())) {
            queryBuilder.append(queryConfig.getQuery("filterByParam5"));
            params.put("@param5", searchConditions.getParam5());
        }

        SqlQuerySpec querySpec = new SqlQuerySpec(queryBuilder.toString(), params);
        return cosmosContainer.queryItems(querySpec, new CosmosQueryRequestOptions(), MyEntity.class)
                .stream().collect(Collectors.toList());
    }
}

💡 Key Features:

✅ Loads queries from queries.properties dynamically.
✅ Constructs SQL query dynamically based on provided parameters.
✅ Uses SqlQuerySpec for parameterized execution (prevents SQL Injection).
✅ Leverages Cosmos SDK (queryItems) for efficient querying.

4️⃣ Service Layer

@Service
public class MyEntityService {

    @Autowired
    private MyEntityCosmosRepository customRepository;

    public List<MyEntity> searchEntities(SearchConditionsDTO searchConditions) {
        if (searchConditions.allFieldsNull()) {
            throw new BadRequestException("At least one search parameter is required.");
        }
        return customRepository.searchWithDynamicQuery(searchConditions);
    }
}

5️⃣ Controller Layer

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/search")
public class MyEntityController {

    @Autowired
    private MyEntityService service;

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<?> search(@RequestBody SearchConditionsDTO searchConditions) {
        List<MyEntity> results = service.searchEntities(searchConditions);

        if (results.isEmpty()) {
            return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND)
                    .body(new ErrorResponseDTO("404", "No results found"));
        }

        return ResponseEntity.ok(results);
    }
}

🚀 Why This is a Real-World Production Approach

✅ Query externalization → SQL queries are stored in properties, making it easy to update without redeployment.
✅ Dynamic SQL Query Generation → Queries adjust dynamically based on user input.
✅ Secure and Efficient → Uses parameterized queries with SqlQuerySpec to prevent SQL Injection.
✅ Cosmos SDK Optimized → Uses queryItems() method with proper RU (Request Unit) efficiency.
✅ Scalable → Handles 1 to 5 optional parameters dynamically.

